---
import CourseLayout from '../../layouts/CourseLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'fine-tuning', label: 'Fine-Tuning' },
  { id: 'at-scale', label: 'Working at Scale' },
  { id: 'validation', label: 'Validation' },
  { id: 'social-science', label: 'Putting It Together' },
];

const math = {
  sftLoss: String.raw`$$\mathcal{L}_{\text{SFT}} = -\sum_{t=1}^{T} \log P_\theta(y_t \mid y_{\lt t}, x)$$`,
  sftCaption: String.raw`The model (with parameters $\theta$) is trained to predict each response token $y_t$ given the instruction $x$ and all preceding response tokens. This is the same next-token prediction objective from pre-training, applied to curated instruction&ndash;response pairs.`,
  loraUpdate: String.raw`$$W' = W + \Delta W = W + BA, \quad B \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times r},\; A \in \mathbb{R}^{r \times d},\; r \ll d$$`,
  loraCaption: String.raw`The original weight matrix $W$ is frozen. The update $\Delta W$ is decomposed into two small matrices $B$ and $A$ whose product has the same shape as $W$. The rank $r$ is typically 8&ndash;64, far smaller than the hidden dimension $d$ (often 4096 or more). For self-attention, the Q, K, V, and O projections are $d \times d$, so both adapter matrices share the same outer dimension. This reduces trainable parameters by a factor of 100&ndash;1000&times;.`,
  encoderClassification: String.raw`$$P(y \mid x) = \text{softmax}\!\left(W_c \cdot \mathbf{h}_{\text{[CLS]}} + b\right)$$`,
  encoderCaption: String.raw`The encoder produces a contextualised hidden state $\mathbf{h}_{\text{[CLS]}}$ for the special classification token. A learned linear layer $W_c$ maps this single vector to a probability distribution over the label set. The entire model (encoder and classification head) is fine-tuned end-to-end.`,
  cohensKappa: String.raw`$$\kappa = \frac{p_o - p_e}{1 - p_e}$$`,
  kappaCaption: String.raw`$p_o$ is the observed agreement between two coders (the proportion of items on which they agree). $p_e$ is the agreement expected by chance, calculated from the marginal distributions of each coder&rsquo;s labels. A $\kappa$ of 1.0 means perfect agreement; 0.0 means agreement no better than chance; negative values indicate systematic disagreement.`,
  f1: String.raw`$$F_1 = 2 \cdot \frac{\text{precision} \cdot \text{recall}}{\text{precision} + \text{recall}}$$`,
  f1Caption: String.raw`Precision is the fraction of predicted positives that are actually positive. Recall is the fraction of actual positives that the model found. $F_1$ is their harmonic mean: it penalises models that sacrifice one metric for the other. Report per-class $F_1$ to detect imbalanced performance.`,
  krippendorff: String.raw`$$\alpha = 1 - \frac{D_o}{D_e}$$`,
  krippendorffCaption: String.raw`$D_o$ is the observed disagreement and $D_e$ is the disagreement expected by chance. Unlike Cohen&rsquo;s $\kappa$, Krippendorff&rsquo;s $\alpha$ handles any number of coders, accommodates missing data, and works with nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio scales.`,
};
---

<CourseLayout
  day={3}
  title="Deploying for Research"
  description="Fine-tuning, working at scale, and validation: building rigorous classification pipelines from prompt to production."
  sections={sections}
>

  <!-- ===================================================================
       DAY INTRODUCTION
       =================================================================== -->
  <div class="day-intro">
    <p>
      In <a href="/course/day-2">Day 2</a>, you built a prompt, chose a
      model, and classified a sample of texts. You also manually labelled
      tweets yourself, the first step toward comparing your judgment
      to the model&rsquo;s. Today starts from that comparison and asks a
      harder question: can you turn that prototype into a
      <strong>research instrument</strong> you would stake a publication on?
    </p>
    <p>
      Doing so requires three capabilities: adapting models to your specific
      task when prompting hits a ceiling, running them reliably at the scale
      your corpus demands, and, most critically, verifying
      that the results are trustworthy enough to build an argument on.
    </p>
    <p>
      By the end of this session you will understand <strong>when and how to
      fine-tune</strong> (LoRA, QLoRA, encoder models), how to
      <strong>move from notebook to production</strong> (APIs, batching,
      self-hosted inference), and how to <strong>validate
      rigorously</strong> (kappa, per-class F1, qualitative error analysis).
      The thread connecting all three: the model is a measurement
      instrument, and instruments require calibration.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ===================================================================
       SECTION 1: FINE-TUNING
       =================================================================== -->
  <section id="fine-tuning">
    <h2>Fine-Tuning</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="/course/day-2">Day 2</a> showed how prompting and reasoning
      techniques turn a language model into a classification instrument. For
      many tasks, this works well. But prompting has a ceiling: when your
      classification scheme is domain-specific, when the model makes
      systematic errors that better examples cannot fix, or when per-token
      costs make API-based prompting prohibitive at scale,
      <strong>fine-tuning</strong> adapts a model&rsquo;s weights to your
      specific task.
    </p>

    <h3>The Decision Framework: Prompt, RAG, or Fine-Tune</h3>
    <p>
      Before investing in fine-tuning, ask whether it is necessary. Three
      approaches exist for improving model performance, and each fits
      different circumstances.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prompting</strong> (covered in
      <a href="/course/day-2#prompting">Day 2</a>) is the right starting
      point when zero-shot or few-shot performance meets your validation
      threshold, when you need flexibility across multiple tasks, when you
      have little or no labeled data, or when the task aligns well with the
      model&rsquo;s pre-training distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)</strong> is the right
      choice when the model needs domain knowledge that exceeds its training
      data or its context window: your corpus of parliamentary records,
      legal texts, or historical archives. RAG uses embeddings (from
      <a href="/course/day-1#embeddings">Day 1</a>) to retrieve relevant
      documents and feed them to the model alongside the query. We cover RAG
      in <a href="/course/day-4">Day 4</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Fine-tuning</strong> is the right choice when prompting
      produces systematic errors that more or better examples cannot resolve,
      when you need consistent output formatting across thousands of
      classifications, when you have labeled data (hundreds to thousands of
      examples), or when domain-specific language or conventions are not
      handled well by general-purpose models.
    </p>

