    <div class="lora-method__body">
      <p>These are <strong>rough planning estimates</strong>, not benchmarked measurements. Actual VRAM depends on your framework (Unsloth, PEFT, Axolotl), batch size, sequence length, gradient checkpointing settings, and other factors. Use these numbers to decide which hardware tier to target, then verify with a short test run.</p>
      <p><strong>Trainable parameters.</strong> LoRA injects two matrices <code>B (d &times; r)</code> and <code>A (r &times; d)</code> into each target projection. We assume 4 target modules per layer (Q, K, V, O). Total trainable = <code>2 &times; d &times; r &times; 4 &times; num_layers</code>.</p>
      <p><strong>Base model memory.</strong> fp16/bf16: 2 bytes/param. 4-bit (QLoRA): &asymp;0.55 bytes/param (includes NF4 quantisation metadata).</p>
      <p><strong>Adapter + optimizer.</strong> LoRA adapters in fp16 (2 bytes/param) plus AdamW states (8 bytes/param) = 10 bytes per trainable parameter.</p>
      <p><strong>Activations.</strong> QLoRA with gradient checkpointing, bs=1, seq=512: &asymp;<code>total_params_B &times; 0.7</code> GB (capped at 20 GB). fp16 LoRA: &asymp;<code>total_params_B &times; 1.0</code> GB (capped at 30 GB). Heuristics calibrated against <a href="https://github.com/unslothai/unsloth" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Unsloth</a> and <a href="https://github.com/huggingface/peft" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PEFT</a> documentation.</p>
      <p><strong>Hardware thresholds.</strong> &check; feasible if VRAM &le; 75% of capacity. &bull; tight if &le; 95%. &cross; insufficient above that.</p>
      <p><strong>Model architectures.</strong> Hidden dimensions and layer counts from published Hugging Face model configs.</p>
    </div>
